notes.text:
An update for kernel is now available for Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6.7 Extended Update Support.

Red Hat Product Security has rated this update as having a security impact of Important. A Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) base score, which gives a detailed severity rating, is available for each vulnerability from the CVE link(s) in the References section.
notes.title: Topic

notes.text:
The kernel packages contain the Linux kernel, the core of any Linux operating system.

Security Fix(es):

* A flaw was found in the Linux kernel's keyring handling code, where in key_reject_and_link() an uninitialized variable would eventually lead to arbitrary free address which could allow attacker to use a use-after-free style attack. (CVE-2016-4470, Important)

This issue was discovered by David Howells (Red Hat Inc.).

acknowledgments.summary: This issue was discovered by Red Hat.

cwe.name: Incorrect Check of Function Return Value

notes.text: A flaw was found in the Linux kernel's keyring handling code: the key_reject_and_link() function could be forced to free an arbitrary memory block. An attacker could use this flaw to trigger a use-after-free condition on the system, potentially allowing for privilege escalation.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: kernel: Uninitialized variable in request_key handling causes kernel crash in error handling path
notes.title: Vulnerability summary

notes.text:
This issue affects the Linux kernels as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6 and may be addressed in a future update.

This issue does not affect the Linux kernel packages as shipped with Red Hat
Enterprise Linux 7 and Red Hat Enterprise MRG 2 as the due updates to fix
this issue have been shipped now.
notes.title: Statement

notes.text: The CVSS score(s) listed for this vulnerability do not reflect the associated product's status, and are included for informational purposes to better understand the severity of this vulnerability.
notes.title: CVSS score applicability

remediations.details:
For details on how to apply this update, which includes the changes described in this advisory, refer to:

https://access.redhat.com/articles/11258

The system must be rebooted for this update to take effect.
